elements.content: Six tetranuclear cadmium(II) complexes, Na[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4(NO3)]·8H2O (1), Na[Cd4(hmt)2(CH3OH)2(H2O)4(dpa)4I]·8H2O (2), Na[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4Br]·8H2O (3), Na2[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4(SCN)2]·4H2O (4), {Na[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4Cl](H2O)4} n (5), and {[Cd4(hmt)3(H2O)5(dpa)4](H2O)10} n (6) (hmt = hexamethylenetetramine, H2dpa = diphenic acid), were synthesized by reactions of H2dpa, hmt, and CdX2 (X = NO3 -, I-, Br-, Cl-, SCN-, and OAc-). All the complexes contain a basic unit [Cd4(dpa)4], in which four dpa ligands in a chelating bis-bidentate coordination mode link two six-coordinate and two seven-coordinate cadmium(II) centers. The research result demonstrates that the nature of the counterions has an important effect on the assembly process of neutral and anionic mixed ligands with metal ions. In 1−3, NO3 -, I-, or Br- bridges the two seven-coordinate CdII centers of the unit to form a discrete tetranuclear molecule with a cis-conformation and hmt as a terminal ligand coordinated to each of the two six-coordinate cadmium(II) centers. Two SCN- in 4 acting as terminal ligands generate a discrete trans-conformational tetranuclear cluster anion. The hmt in 5 acting as a μ-ligand links cis-conformational tetranuclear units by Cd−N bonds to generate a one-dimensional chain structure, while the hmt in 6 acting as a μ-ligand links the tetranuclear units by Cd−N bonds to generate a two-dimensional layer structure composed of a planar-conformation [Cd4(dpa)4] unit. The fluorescent studies in the solid at room temperature show that the six complexes exhibit strong violet or blue emissions in the range 370−500 nm arising from the charge-transfer transition and that the bridging anions have a significant effect on their fluorescent properties.

elements.content: During the past decade, the controlled self-assembly of metallosupramolecular complexes has attracted great attentions from chemists owing to their intriguing structural topologies and their potential application as functional materials. So far, considerable progress has been achieved in dominating assembly and orientation of individual building blocks into structures with specific topologies and functions including ion/molecular recognition, ion exchange, selective guest inclusion, etc. The most common approach to build supramolecular architectures is the rational combination of organic ligands containing appropriate coordination sites and metal ions bearing a specific coordination geometry. In this regard, two types of supramolecular frameworks, discrete coordination architectures and infinite polymeric networks, can be produced in the similar reactions, respectively. A lot of one-, two-, and three-dimensional structural motifs have also been constructed from discrete complexes through the additional peripheral binding sites in the ligands coordinating to metal centers or counteranions further bridging metal centers. Likewise, discrete complexes and infinite polymers can also be obtained through controlling coordination modes of ligands in both neutral and anionic mixed bridging ligands. However, the systematic research on this subject from the combination of metal ions with mixed ligands is much less explored owing to difficult prediction and control of the compositions or the structures of final products, despite the fact that metal−organic frameworks constructed by mixed ligands are more adjustable than a single ligand. Moreover, although a lot of interesting metal−organic frameworks have been constructed from mixed ligands, the effects of the counteranions on the assembly process of anionic and neutral mixed ligands with metal ions have also seldom been investigated. Hence, it is a challenge to predict and control the exactly discrete coordination architectures or infinite polymeric networks through the self-assembly process of metal ions and mixed ligands in crystal engineering since the structures are highly influenced by the coordination preferences of metal ions, the nature of organic ligands, and some very subtle factors, such as counteranions.

Introduction

During the past decade, the controlled self-assembly of metallosupramolecular complexes has attracted great attentions from chemists owing to their intriguing structural topologies and their potential application as functional materials. So far, considerable progress has been achieved in dominating assembly and orientation of individual building blocks into structures with specific topologies and functions including ion/molecular recognition, ion exchange, selective guest inclusion, etc. The most common approach to build supramolecular architectures is the rational combination of organic ligands containing appropriate coordination sites and metal ions bearing a specific coordination geometry. In this regard, two types of supramolecular frameworks, discrete coordination architectures and infinite polymeric networks, can be produced in the similar reactions, respectively. A lot of one-, two-, and three-dimensional structural motifs have also been constructed from discrete complexes through the additional peripheral binding sites in the ligands coordinating to metal centers or counteranions further bridging metal centers. Likewise, discrete complexes and infinite polymers can also be obtained through controlling coordination modes of ligands in both neutral and anionic mixed bridging ligands. However, the systematic research on this subject from the combination of metal ions with mixed ligands is much less explored owing to difficult prediction and control of the compositions or the structures of final products, despite the fact that metal-organic frameworks constructed by mixed ligands are more adjustable than a single ligand. Moreover, although a lot of interesting metal-organic frameworks have been constructed from mixed ligands, the effects of the counteranions on the assembly process of anionic and neutral mixed ligands with metal ions have also seldom been investigated. Hence, it is a challenge to predict and control the exactly discrete coordination architectures or infinite polymeric networks through the self-assembly process of metal ions and mixed ligands in crystal engineering since the structures are highly influenced by the coordination preferences of metal ions, the nature of organic ligands, and some very subtle factors, such as counteranions.

elements.content: In the design and synthesis of metal−oorganic complexes, diphenic acid (H2dpa) is an excellent aromatic dicarboxylic ligand, in which two phenyl rings are not coplanar with each other owing to the steric hindrance of 2,2‘-positioned carboxylate groups in the coordination process. The distortion of the diphenyl spacer about the central bond can result in formation of discrete complexes and infinite polymers in the course of assembly with metal ions. Meanwhile, hexamethylenetetramine (hmt) is another candidate for the neutral bridging ligand, which can adopt a potential terminal, μ2-, μ3-, or μ4-bridging mode; moreover, hmt can act as an acceptor of a hydrogen bond to generate hydrogen bonding networks. The combination of dpa, hmt, and metal ions can produce some unique frameworks with beautiful aesthetics and useful properties. However, to the best our knowledge, no example of this type of complexes has been reported to date, although many complexes have been designed and constructed through the mixed ligands of both dpa and neutral bridging ligands, such as 4,4-bipyridine and 1,2-di(4-pyridyl)ethylene. Herein, we wish to report the syntheses and characterizations of a series of CdII complexes exhibiting three different types of topologies, Na[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4(NO3)]·8H2O (1), Na[Cd4(hmt)2(CH3OH)2(H2O)4(dpa)4I]·8H2O (2), Na[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4Br]·8H2O (3), Na2[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4(SCN)2]·4H2O (4), {Na[Cd4(hmt)2(H2O)6(dpa)4Cl](H2O)4} n (5), and {[Cd4(hmt)3(H2O)5(dpa)4](H2O)10} n (6), which were synthesized through reactions of H2dpa, hmt, and CdX2 (X = NO3 -, I-, Br-, Cl-, SCN-, and OAc-).

X-ray Data Collection and Structure Determination. All intensity data were measured on a Siemens Smart CCD diffractometer with graphite-monochromated Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.710 73 Å) at room temperature, except complex 2 was measured on a Bruker CCD diffractometer. All empirical absorption corrections were applied by using the SADABS program. The structures were solved by direct methods and refined using the SHELXL-97 program package. CdII atoms in each complex were located from E-maps, and other non-hydrogen atoms were located in successive difference Fourier syntheses. The final refinement was performed by full-matrix least-squares methods with anisotropic thermal parameters for non-hydrogen atoms on F 2. The positions of H atoms were generated geometrically (C−H bond fixed at 0.96 Å), assigned isotropic thermal parameters, and allowed to ride on their parent carbon atoms before the final cycle of refinement. Synthesis and Characterization. Reaction of H2dpa, hmt, and Cd(NO3)2·4H2O in the presence of NaOH in MeOH/H2O (2:1) produced a discrete complex consisting of an isolated cis-conformational tetrameric cadmium(II) anion, in which NO3 - bridges two adjacent CdII centers. As known, not only can counteranions keep balance of charge as the soft or hard nucleophiles, but also their coordination ability, size, and template effects have important influences on structural frameworks of supramolecular complexes. The successful synthesis of 1 by using a hard counterion NO3 - prompts us to investigate the effect of the soft counterions, such as I-, Br-, Cl-, and SCN-, on assembly products of mixed ligands and CdII for 2−5. Reactions of H2dpaand hmt with CdI2 and CdBr2·4H2O afforded discrete complexes of 2 and 3 with the same cis-conformational tetrameric cadmium(II) anion as that in 1. However, reaction of H2dpa and hmt with CdCl2·2.5H2O produced a one-dimensional chain complex 5 consisting of cis-conformational tetrameric cadmium(II) anions bridged by hmt. In complexes 1−3 and 5, NO3 -, I-, Br-, and Cl- act as μ-ligands, and the Cd···Cd separations across them are 5.503, 5.323, 5.016, and 4.900 Å, respectively. The cis-conformations in 1−3 and 5 are mainly ascribed to the similar effective anionic radii in aqueous solutions of NO3 -, I-, Br-, and Cl- (about 3.0 Å), despite their different nucleophilic features. It was expected that with larger effective anionic radius in aqueous solution the soft or hard nucleophiles may result in different structural frameworks. Actually, when SCN- (about 3.5 Å) was employed as the larger soft counterion, a discrete complex with a trans-conformational tetranuclear cadmium(II) anion was obtained, in which SCN- acts as a terminal ligand through one nitrogen atom coordinating to a CdII center. When CH3COO-, a hard counterion with large size, was used under the same reaction conditions, a two-dimensional layer complex 6 consisting of Cd4 entities bridged by μ-hmt was afforded, in which CH3COO- has not been involved in crystallization.

Single-crystal X-ray diffraction analysis reveals that complex 1 crystallizes in the orthorhombic space group Cmcm. The crystal structure consists of a tetranuclear [Cd4(hmt)2(dpa)4(NO3)(H2O)6]- anion with cis-conformation, an isolated Na+, and eight water molecules of crystallization. As shown in Figure a, there are two crystallographically independent CdII centers occupying sites with mirror symmetry in the anionic framework. Cd(1) adopts a distorted pentagonal pyramidal geometry in a CdO5N fashion, in which two asymmetrically chelating carboxylate groups from different dpa's and one nitrogen atom of hmt comprise the equatorial basal plane and one water molecule occupies the apical position [Cd(1)−OW1 = 2.334(6) Å]. However, Cd(2) is in a distorted pentagonal bipyramidal geometry with two asymmetrically chelating carboxylate groups from different dpa's and one oxygen atom from the bridging NO3 - occupying the equatorial basal plane and two water molecules at the apical sites [OW2−Cd(2)−OW3 = 153.9(3)°]. The chelating distortion of the carboxylate groups may be attributed to five coordinated atoms occupying the equatorial basal plane. The deviations of Cd(1) and Cd(2) from the equatorial basal plane toward axial atoms are 0.0640 and 0.2607 Å, respectively. The Cd−O(carboxylate) bond distances are in the range from 2.224(4) to 2.526(4) Å, which are similar to the documented Cd−O(carboxylate) distances [2.251−2.879 Å]. Dpa behaves as a chelating bis-bidentate mode (Scheme a); the carboxylate groups chelating with Cd(1) and Cd(2) are twisted with respect to correspondingly linking phenyl rings with the dihedral angles between them being 40.3 and 44.1°, respectively, and a slightly dramatic twist between the two phenyl rings of dpa is also observed with the dihedral angle between them being 56.2°. The combination of these twists is favorable for the formation of the tetranuclear cadmium(II) framework. Hmt serves as a terminal ligand through one of the nitrogen atoms coordinating to six-coordinate Cd(1) with the Cd−N bond distance being 2.506(6) Å. It should be emphasized that NO3 - not only serves as a counteranion but, most of all, it also acts as a μ-ligand to connect two seven-coordinate CdII centers, which results in formation of the framework with a cis-conformation (Figure b). The Cd(2)··· Cd(2A) separation across the NO3 - is 5.503 Å, which is significantly shorter than the Cd(1)···Cd(1A) separation of 8.428 Å and is similar to the Cd(1)···Cd(2) separation bridged by dpa (5.774 Å). It is noteworthy that three water molecules coordinated with the adjacent carboxylate oxygen atoms [OW1-H···O22 = 2.798; OW1-H···O22A = 2.798; OW2-H···O12 = 2.750; OW2-H···O12B = 2.750 Å], and the adjacent uncoordinated water molecules [OW3···OW4 = 2.782; OW3···OW4B = 2.782 Å] form O−H···O hydrogen bonds; such hydrogen bonding interactions consolidate the tetrameric anionic framework (Figure c). There are no other short contacts or noteworthy aryl−aryl interactions between the adjacent tetranuclear cadmium(II) frameworks.

The data of the emission spectra for complexes 1−6 and ligand H2dpa in the solid state at room temperature are listed in Table (note that the ligand hmt has no emission). Interestingly, they exhibit different fluorescent properties (Figure ). Complex 1 shows two strong violet emission bands with the maximum intensity at 379 and 416 nm upon excitation at 328 nm. Complex 2 gives two peaks at 374 and 511 nm when irradiated at 326 nm. Complexes 3 and 5 give a main peak with a weaker shoulder occurring at 395 and 485 nm for 3 and 418 and 496 nm for 5 when irradiated at 335 and 340 nm, respectively. Complex 4 gives a strong blue emission band with the maximum intensity at 440 nm (λex = 328 nm). However, an intense purple emission for 6 is observed at 385 nm (λex = 328 nm). In comparison with that of free H2dpa (an intense emission at 459 nm (λex = 310 nm), which is attributed to the π* → π transition), an obvious hypsochromic shift of the main emissions in 1−6 was observed, but the nature of the emissions (379, 374, 395, 440, 418, and 385 nm for 1−6, respectively) may be attributed to metal-perturbed intraligand emissions of dpa. As known, the intraligand emissions for the same ligand can be tuned by its conformations. For dpa in complexes 1−6, its conformations sharply alter with the dihedral angles of the phenyl rings of dpa from 56.2 to 86.0° due to coordination, which thus results in the changes of the intraligand emissions of dpa. The observation of almost the same emission in complexes 1 and 2 or in complexes 4 and 5, where dpa has similar conformations with almost the same dihedral angles of the phenyl rings, further proves the above point. Conclusions

In this paper, we have successfully prepared six cadmium(II) complexes by using the soft counterions (I-, Br-, Cl-, and SCN-) or hard counterions (NO3 - and CH3COO-) with different effective anionic radii in aqueous solution. Complexes 1-3 and 5 comprise cis-conformational tetranuclear cadmium(II) anions with m symmetry, 4 consists of an isolate tetranuclear cadmium(II) anion with a trans-conformation, and 6 is a two-dimensional layer structure composed of Cd4 entities bridged by μ-hmt. This research demonstrates that the nature of the counterions has an important effect on the assembly process of neutral and anionic mixed ligands with metal ions. The counterions with different sizes and different nucleophilic features can result in supramolecular architectures with different structures and functions. Moreover, the successful preparation of these complexes provides a valuable approach for the construction of many other metal-organic frameworks from anionic and neutral mixed ligands. The fluorescent studies of the six complexes in the solid state at room temperature show that the emissions probably arise from the charge-transfer transition and the counteranions have a very important effect on their fluorescent properties.
